In [45]:
train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(                                                      # Creating an ImageDataGenerator with data augmentation
    rescale=1./255,                                                                      # Rescaling the pixel values to be in the range [0, 1] 
    rotation_range=40,                                                                   # Rotating the images randomly by a maximum of 40 degrees
    width_shift_range=0.2,                                                               # Shifting the width of the image by a maximum of 20% of its total width
    height_shift_range=0.2,                                                              # Shifting the height of the image by a maximum of 20% of its total height
    shear_range=0.2,                                                                     # Shearing transformation with a maximum shear intensity of 20%
    zoom_range=0.2,                                                                      # Zooming in or out randomly by a maximum of 20%
    horizontal_flip=True,                                                                # Randomly flipping the images horizontally
    fill_mode='nearest'                                                                  # Filling in any empty pixels created by the above transformations with the nearest pixel value
)

The Keras provides a variety of data augmentation methods through the ImageDataGenerator class. Some of them are,

  1. Rescaling
  2. Geometric Transformations
  3. Flip Operations
  4. Brightness and Contrast Adjustments
  5. Fill Mode
  6. Normalization

Rescale: The pixel values are typically in the range of 0 to 255. By dividing all pixel values by 255 the normalizing of the pixel values to be in the range [0, 1]. This helps the optimization algorithm converge faster during training.

train_generator = train_datagen.flow_from_directory(                                     # Creating a data generator for training images with data augmentation
    data_dir.joinpath(split),                                                            # Path to the directory containing training images
    target_size=(224, 224),                                                              # Reshaping the images to a consistent size of 224x224 pixels
    batch_size=32,                                                                       # The number of images in each batch
    class_mode='categorical',                                                            # Type of label assignment for classification task
    classes=[class_name for class_name, _ in top_three_classes]                          # Using only the top three classes
)

def plot_images(images, labels):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
    for i in range(min(9, len(images))):
        plt.subplot(3, 3, i + 1)                                                    # Creating a subplot in a 3x3 grid (index 'i + 1' is used to position the subplot)
        plt.imshow(images[i])                                                       # For displaying the image at index i within the subplot
        plt.title(labels[i])                                                        # Setting the title of the subplot
        plt.axis("off")                                                             # Turning off axis labels and ticks for the subplot
    
    plt.show()                                                                      # Displaying the entire plot with the grid of images and labels

augmentedImages, augmentedLabels = next(train_generator)                            # Getting the next batch of augmented images and labels from the train_generator
classLabels = list(train_generator.class_indices.keys())                            # Retrieving class labels from the train_generator
augmentedClassNames = [classLabels[np.argmax(label)] for label in augmentedLabels]  # Converting one-hot encoded labels to class names for the augmented images

plot_images(augmentedImages, augmentedClassNames)                                   # Calling the plot_images function to display the grid of augmented images and their class names
In [48]:
base_model = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(224, 224, 3))                        # Loading the VGG16 model with pre-trained ImageNet weights, excluding the top classification layer and also setting the input shape to (224, 224, 3)

for layer in base_model.layers:                                                                             # Freezing the weights of all layers in the base model so they are not updated during training
    layer.trainable = False

model = models.Sequential()                                                                                 # Creating a sequential model

model.add(base_model)                                                                                       # Adding the pre-trained VGG16 base model to the sequential model

model.add(layers.Flatten())                                                                                 # Flattening the output of the VGG16 base model

model.add(layers.Dense(256, activation='relu'))                                                             # Adding a dense layer with 256 neurons and ReLU activation function

model.add(layers.Dense(len(top_three_classes), activation='softmax'))                                       # The final dense layer with the number of neurons equal to the number of classes in top_three_classes and use softmax activation for multi-class classification

model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])                      # Compiling the model with the Adam optimizer, categorical crossentropy loss, and accuracy as the metric

history = model.fit(train_generator, epochs=10, validation_data=train_generator)                            # Training the model on the training data using the fit method, specifying the number of epochs and the validation data

In [52]:
# Convert true_labels and predicted_labels to binary format
binarized_true_labels = label_binarize(true_labels, classes=[0, 1, 2])                          # Binarize true labels
binarized_predicted_labels = label_binarize(predicted_labels, classes=[0, 1, 2])                # Binarize predicted labels

# Plot precision-recall curve
precision = dict()
recall = dict()
pr_auc = dict()

for i in range(len(top_three_classes)):
    precision[i], recall[i], _ = precision_recall_curve(binarized_true_labels[:, i], binarized_predicted_labels[:, i])
    pr_auc[i] = auc(recall[i], precision[i])

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
for i in range(len(top_three_classes)):
    plt.plot(recall[i], precision[i], label=f'Class {i} (AUC = {pr_auc[i]:.2f})')               # Plot precision-recall curves

plt.xlabel('Recall')
plt.ylabel('Precision')
plt.title('Precision-Recall Curve')
plt.legend()
plt.show()
